## Web2 hosting

![](broken_metadata.png) ([source](https://twitter.com/jacobdotsol/status/1600526700982710273))

There seems to be a general consensus in the NFT space that IPFS (or Arweave) are the proper ways to host your metadata and images as they are more resilient and allow others to host or "pin" the content to ensure it's availability. In the FTX example above, the content wasn't being hosted on IPFS at all, instead just being served from some backend application hosted by FTX. After their insolvency and corporate takeover, the site is now redirecting elsewhere, meaning all the NFT metadata is unavailable and the NFTs from there are, in a sense, "dead".

However, some people falsely assume that using IPFS is a fool-proof way to immortalize data. 

While IPFS is great and a step above directly hosting via a web server/service, it still requires at least 1 person to have a copy of the content on their IPFS gateway. It's similar to torrenting where if nobody is "seeding" the torrent, nobody else can download it. If content stops being "pinned" and requested in IPFS, the content ceases to exist until someone "pins" it again or even just has a copy of it.


## HTTP IPFS Gateway != IPFS

Even some of the largest teams seem to be using IPFS but in a way that is still extremely centralized. Here is [one example](https://twitter.com/CardilloSamuel/status/1398516076732993536?s=20&t=ykz921dTMBzi5VcS8B0Zwg):

![](rtfkt_tweet.png)
![](https://pbs.twimg.com/media/E2iGzIsWEAA7vQn?format=jpg&name=4096x4096)
![](https://pbs.twimg.com/media/E2iGzIsWEAEJoqh?format=jpg&name=4096x4096)

While yes, the content is hosted on IPFS, it's also being served from the Pinata IPFS hosting web service (`https://rtfkt.mypinata.cloud`) that probably some crazy high percentage of other projects are using (my own projects included).

That means that the content hosted this way can be interrupted if:
* RTFKT team stops paying their bill to Pinata
* Pinata suffers from an outage or data loss event on their platform ([it can happen](https://www.datacenterknowledge.com/archives/2017/03/02/aws-outage-that-broke-the-internet-caused-by-mistyped-command))
* Pinata performs accidental DNS changes 
* Pinata forgets to pay their domain name registration ([it can happen](https://www.theverge.com/2016/1/29/10868404/google-reveals-how-much-it-paid-the-guy-who-bought-google-com/))
* The underlying infrastructure or cloud provider of Pinata experiences an outage or data loss event
* Pinata forgets to renew the TLS certificate associated with that endpoint
* etc

There are probably a dozen more ways pointing at a clearnet URL could impact service. (I'm not picking on RTFKT or "fudding" or anything, they were just the first example I found while searching on Twitter.) This is just the nature of legacy, "web2", internet infrastructure. It's all extremely centralized and dependent on other entities for reliance. That's partly why I'm such a big fan of crypto and the push for decentralizing and decoupling people, technology, corporations, governments, etc. 

The only saving grace is that due to the popularity of the project, any sort of outage or incident wouldn't be a huge deal because so many **platforms** have copies of the content.

Emphasis on the word **platforms**.


## When keeping it real goes wrong

This is what happens for unpopular projects. I ran a meme site that would upload images and metadata to IPFS, then mint tokens on the [Avalanche network](https://snowtrace.io/address/0x60bde7a29c653142bbab1fe094016af2f4776158). I shut down the service and deleted the VPS thinking I didn't need it anymore but forgot it was the only thing pinning hashes. When Opensea added the integration for AVAX I was pleasantly surprised to see my tokens, but later disappointed to see my [broken, "dead", NFTs](https://opensea.io/collection/suchwowx).

Many of the NFTs that I had minted there no longer have valid metadata or images because the content on IPFS doesn't exist! Someone would have to locate the source images, regenerate the JSON metadata, and upload them exactly as they were (to get the same hash).

![](broken_avax.png)

![](avax_tokenuri.png)


## On-chain is the best?

On-chain, AKA, keeping all of the content data inside of a smart contract's storage is pretty much the ideal...no dependencies on anything besides the blockchain in question going away. 

If for whatever reason the Ethereum network was killed....would your NFTs matter anyways? 

{% image() %}
steve_harvey.png
{% end %}

While it is ideal, it's not always feasible. Cost is a huge prohibiting factor in this, especially for generative projects. If a project is rendering ten thousand pictures of monkey jpegs, trying to store each one on-chain would be [hella expensive](https://ethereum.stackexchange.com/questions/872/what-is-the-cost-to-store-1kb-10kb-100kb-worth-of-data-into-the-ethereum-block)...so if each monkey picture was one megabyte in size it would cost roughly.....$760,000.

Even using more efficient means of layering like with vector images, it's pretty expensive. The [CyberBrokers](https://www.cyberbrokers.com/) project recently put all of their artwork on-chain and it cost them [about $250,000](https://dappradar.com/blog/why-cyberbrokers-paid-250000-to-make-nfts-completely-on-chain).



Even simpler projects, like my own [TulipMania!](https://tulipmanianft.xyz/), was costly to deploy. I pushed several layers of SVG into the [smart contract](https://etherscan.io/address/0x3d2da31a3253b54bfdc11561ecbabd42b15daf14) (different pieces of the tulip, background, styles and animations, bubbles, shadows, etc) and it cost about .8 ETH all in all...chump change compared to CyberBrokers.

Although it was a higher up-front cost, it's now part of the Ethereum blockchain forever....or until it dies or the heat death of the sun and all that.

It does make it easy though! The contract returns JSON metadata right from the `tokenURI` function and the entirety of the SVG data is returned as `base64` encoded data, meaning it can be pasted just like this (right-click, inspect element):

{% image() %}
data:image/svg+xml;base64,
{% end %}

Aint it pretty?

If you want to learn more about on-chain NFTs, would highly recommend reading [this blog post](https://blog.simondlr.com/posts/flavours-of-on-chain-svg-nfts-on-ethereum) by a crypto OG who paved the way for us.


## In short

I guess my points are:

* Using HTTP endpoints isn't decentralized at all; someone is paying the bill for hosting and it can be taken offline at any time; point your contract's `tokenURI` to `ipfs://<hash>` instead
* IPFS isn't the best solution but it's a much better option; someone usually still pays the bill for hosting/pinning, but at least everyone else can keep copies available
* On-chain is ideal, but difficult and expensive, not typically feasible, especially for PFP projects
* More people should be pinning content locally for the resilience of the content they like and the creators they support (not easy for noobs at the moment)
* There should be less reliance on large platforms (corporations)

The NFT scene would do well to decouple from legacy "web2" internet infrastructure as much as possible (the NFT scene is basically powered by large corporations: Opensea, AWS, Twitter, and Discord)

Wen wallets that pin hashes for you along with displaying the images/content? Wen decentralized marketplaces? Wen open source galleries compatible with any/all projects?

We need an "ez-mode IPFS tool" that projects push for their patrons to pin content so everyone can contribute something to further the push closer to decentralization.
